  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "VL",
    "text": "Which is now encased in plastic for the reason of preservation. But inside you see a little ring. Looks duraluminum, like silver color. And it is part of the buzz bombs that the Germans sent over London, during World War II. And there must have been dozens of those little rings, as parts of the-- as they call them-- [GERMAN]. And at the concentration camp annex of the tunnel, at the Nordhausen Dora, my job was measuring these rings by the hundreds, with a micro-- micrometric screw. And of course, that was a very easy job to sabotage. Because instead of measuring the exact measurements, we just said, oh, this is-- doesn't fit, and we discarded half of them. There were several of us that did the same job in the tunnel at Dora camp.",
